1
00:00:00,402 --> 00:00:27,658
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:27,992 --> 00:00:33,863
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,884 --> 00:00:35,767
So we have a few questions here.

4
00:00:35,786 --> 00:00:37,409
Let's see how we can get on with them.

5
00:00:38,110 --> 00:00:39,514
The first one is about emotions.

6
00:00:41,957 --> 00:00:43,140
So they're conditioned.

7
00:00:43,962 --> 00:00:48,710
So how can they arise when we meditate in the present moment?

8
00:00:49,411 --> 00:00:51,756
Is it because we're not fully in the present moment?

9
00:00:54,588 --> 00:01:02,476
Well, in vipassana, remember, we are standing off from the whole organism.

10
00:01:02,698 --> 00:01:11,188
We've found a place, this observation post, this place within ourselves where we're looking into ourselves.

11
00:01:12,890 --> 00:01:24,222
And emotions, when we actually experience them in the body, are just some form of feeling, aren't they?

12
00:01:24,388 --> 00:01:28,093
We give them a name, might say anxiety, for instance.

13
00:01:29,756 --> 00:01:34,563
But as soon as we give it a name, we slot it into a particular category.

14
00:01:35,284 --> 00:01:37,746
So it becomes unpleasant, et cetera, et cetera.

15
00:01:38,188 --> 00:01:39,530
You can't stop that happening.

16
00:01:39,609 --> 00:01:43,555
That's just part and parcel of recognizing the emotion that's arisen.

17
00:01:44,757 --> 00:01:54,209
Now, because we are standing off the whole process, the whole process that's going on psychologically and physically,

18
00:01:55,304 --> 00:01:59,409
the heart expresses whatever turbulence is at the surface.

19
00:02:00,611 --> 00:02:16,135
So these turbulences that we call emotions or moods or whatever, and the thought patterns that go with them are part of that category of the aggregates, the khandhas, which is the sankharas.

20
00:02:16,376 --> 00:02:19,640
The sankharas are something that we manufacture.

21
00:02:20,194 --> 00:02:21,757
All the rest of it is a given.

22
00:02:22,157 --> 00:02:32,850
So the sense base sees something and it moves back into the memory, which is part of our perceptual process.

23
00:02:33,853 --> 00:02:45,848
And then that memory, the image, etc., with the concept or the perception that we have with it,

24
00:02:46,367 --> 00:02:52,574
brings up the feeling tone of what it is that we're experiencing.

25
00:02:53,115 --> 00:02:55,417
And altogether, we just call that a mental state.

26
00:02:55,578 --> 00:03:06,709
And an emotion is pointing to that feeling value, the feeling value, the affected, the affective value of our experience.

27
00:03:08,131 --> 00:03:12,936
And there's no telling what the heart's going to offer.

28
00:03:13,015 --> 00:03:15,277
I mean, this is one of the

29
00:03:16,675 --> 00:03:28,152
understandings we have that we don't actually know ourselves in that way so you're sitting there and just out of the blue some memory comes from childhood when somebody hit you on the head with a bat

30
00:03:29,145 --> 00:03:30,108
That's what happened to me, you see.

31
00:03:30,388 --> 00:03:31,189
I've never been the same.

32
00:03:32,431 --> 00:03:36,699
And suddenly you remember it.

33
00:03:36,718 --> 00:03:38,481
And I even remember his name, Ken.

34
00:03:38,943 --> 00:03:40,344
And suddenly I think, I'll kill him.

35
00:03:42,609 --> 00:03:45,655
And where's that come from, you see?

36
00:03:45,754 --> 00:03:47,677
It's all mixed up inside yourself.

37
00:03:48,282 --> 00:03:54,008
And then suddenly, for apparently no reason, like just now, I haven't thought of this for years.

38
00:03:54,128 --> 00:03:59,596
It just came up just out of the blue.

39
00:03:59,616 --> 00:04:01,198
And it just comes out of the blue.

40
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:04,241
And then it latches on to an emotion.

41
00:04:04,622 --> 00:04:06,444
Now, that's the important thing to think about.

42
00:04:06,544 --> 00:04:08,848
That's the important thing to realize about an emotion.

43
00:04:09,549 --> 00:04:12,652
The emotional state is not attached to the object.

44
00:04:13,526 --> 00:04:14,588
That's the important thing.

45
00:04:15,912 --> 00:04:28,379
So your emotions, all these things to do with desire, hatred, aversion, fear, etc., etc., are like, I sort of image them like balloons.

46
00:04:29,372 --> 00:04:34,357
And so you've got a balloon of anger and a balloon of excitement and joy, you see.

47
00:04:35,317 --> 00:04:42,704
And what happens is something comes up which puts a little pinprick and all that emotion wants to get out through there.

48
00:04:43,346 --> 00:04:49,591
And that's where we get this sort of inappropriate reaction to things, road rage and stuff like that.

49
00:04:50,512 --> 00:04:57,478
Because the emotion itself is a conditioning that we have developed towards an object.

50
00:04:57,699 --> 00:04:59,379
It's not caused by the object.

51
00:04:59,360 --> 00:05:11,817
so very simply if somebody hits me on the nose the pain stops there it doesn't travel anywhere else it's on the nose and there

52
00:05:12,067 --> 00:05:18,334
the feeling of anger that I get from them, it hits me and I can feel it and it stops there.

53
00:05:18,834 --> 00:05:22,559
But what I do is I react to it with anger or fear.

54
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:30,249
And that's what I'm generating, the anger and fear that I have towards what's coming at me.

55
00:05:30,269 --> 00:05:33,673
Now, that anger and fear is not specific to the object.

56
00:05:33,773 --> 00:05:39,879
It's just something I've developed whenever I see something that's dangerous to me.

57
00:05:41,209 --> 00:05:41,449
Yeah.

58
00:05:42,432 --> 00:05:49,365
So you're sitting there in meditation and there's Ken again with his back and he bonked on it because I beat him, you see.

59
00:05:50,206 --> 00:05:51,990
Well, you know, he's a bad loser.

60
00:05:52,009 --> 00:05:56,838
So, so, so then I think, oh, what's that?

61
00:05:57,274 --> 00:06:11,060
And I think what's happened in my own mind is that the turbulence of anger has sort of begun to rise to the surface of consciousness, of the mind, where it touches consciousness.

62
00:06:11,079 --> 00:06:12,403
And it's seeking an object.

63
00:06:12,802 --> 00:06:14,507
It's seeking something to grab hold of.

64
00:06:14,966 --> 00:06:16,971
So it grabs hold of this memory.

65
00:06:17,221 --> 00:06:18,002
And off you go.

66
00:06:18,182 --> 00:06:28,358
You start then thinking about this memory and you're developing this anger through developing a storyline around this Ken, whom I'm still hunting for.

67
00:06:32,384 --> 00:06:33,846
I sent out a search warrant.

68
00:06:36,610 --> 00:06:44,824
So, it's nothing to do with the observer, the feeler, the one who knows.

69
00:06:46,565 --> 00:06:57,184
Now, normally speaking, you're engaged in the organism and therefore you seem to be, as it were, in charge of your emotions.

70
00:06:57,838 --> 00:07:02,584
So you might say to yourself, well, you know, I'll go to the cinema and I'll watch this film.

71
00:07:02,625 --> 00:07:04,887
It's a horror film and I know it's going to frighten me.

72
00:07:04,947 --> 00:07:06,509
That's great because I like being frightened.

73
00:07:06,870 --> 00:07:08,752
So you sit there and watch the horror film.

74
00:07:09,093 --> 00:07:10,213
So that's your decision.

75
00:07:10,634 --> 00:07:11,415
You've made that.

76
00:07:11,516 --> 00:07:13,137
You seem to be in control of it.

77
00:07:13,918 --> 00:07:22,009
But at other times, for instance, you wake up, you never say that, you know, tomorrow I'm going to wake up depressed.

78
00:07:22,449 --> 00:07:25,533
But you wake up and you're depressed and it's just come up.

79
00:07:25,814 --> 00:07:27,576
It's just come up of its own accord.

80
00:07:28,146 --> 00:07:42,041
And that's what we're discovering, that when you take this position of the observer within yourself, the feeler, remember the awareness is multiple in its sensitivities.

81
00:07:42,062 --> 00:07:45,165
It can feel, it can see, it can understand.

82
00:07:48,389 --> 00:07:51,752
What you're saying to the heart is manifest, manifest yourself.

83
00:07:52,512 --> 00:07:54,475
What have you got hidden from me?

84
00:07:54,454 --> 00:08:23,836
and that remember is the process of therapy yeah we're not doing the practice in order to have psychotherapy or for the mind to heal itself it's just a natural process that the heart does when you come off it the turbulence itself begins to manifest and so long as we don't get lost in that thinking and all that that energy begins to evaporate but it doesn't disappear remember it always moves towards its opposite

85
00:08:24,778 --> 00:08:30,026
So whatever was a hateful, angry mood will move towards love, you see.

86
00:08:33,910 --> 00:08:38,356
I mean, in Zen they say, you know, with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

87
00:08:39,337 --> 00:08:42,522
And we practice metta just to give it a little bit of a push, you know.

88
00:08:43,163 --> 00:08:53,756
But in the process of purifying the heart, in the process whereby the heart purifies itself, it's always moving towards purity naturally.

89
00:08:54,073 --> 00:09:01,240
and towards the virtues.

90
00:09:01,260 --> 00:09:01,341
See?

91
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:02,442
I always say it's very cheap.

92
00:09:06,004 --> 00:09:12,791
So it's nothing to do about being, it is to do specifically about being present in the moment in that particular way.

93
00:09:13,172 --> 00:09:16,075
And the heart then manifests its turbulences.

94
00:09:16,654 --> 00:09:23,000
And it can throw up even traumas from, I mean, real traumas from early life.

95
00:09:23,351 --> 00:09:29,902
can be liberated through this process, yeah?

96
00:09:29,922 --> 00:09:32,205
Are there any questions arising out of that?

97
00:09:35,730 --> 00:09:43,721
So in answer to the question, emotions are conditioned, yes, so how can they arise when we meditate, right?

98
00:09:43,743 --> 00:09:46,086
So they arise of themselves, this is what you realize, yeah?

99
00:09:46,639 --> 00:09:48,282
the knee hurts of itself.

100
00:09:48,642 --> 00:09:51,124
It doesn't ask you for permission, does it?

101
00:09:51,705 --> 00:09:52,605
Do you mind if I scream?

102
00:09:52,946 --> 00:09:53,386
No.

103
00:09:53,407 --> 00:09:54,768
It just starts screaming.

104
00:09:56,590 --> 00:09:58,731
And is it because we're not fully in the present?

105
00:09:58,772 --> 00:10:01,293
No, we are fully in the present, but in a particular way.

106
00:10:02,475 --> 00:10:04,957
We've taken this objective position within ourselves.

107
00:10:05,557 --> 00:10:08,120
That's not the same as being fully present when you're doing something.

108
00:10:08,701 --> 00:10:15,447
Because then you're engaging the organism and it will come up with a certain mental state to support your engagement.

109
00:10:16,221 --> 00:10:29,236
So if you say to yourself, right, I'm going to wash the pots or something, or do this piece of work on the computer, then you are ordering, so we say, the organism to do this particular task.

110
00:10:29,998 --> 00:10:43,494
It might be that during that, you get some little bit of irritation and stuff, which comes up again because of your reaction to what you're doing, or you might just suddenly boredom comes up, all that sort of stuff.

111
00:10:44,034 --> 00:10:45,216
But the point is that

112
00:10:45,482 --> 00:10:53,552
we can use this organism to do stuff.

113
00:10:53,572 --> 00:11:01,740
And that's different from being in this position in ourselves of the objective observer, where we're just leaving the organism alone, you see.

114
00:11:02,280 --> 00:11:03,682
We're just watching the process.

115
00:11:05,865 --> 00:11:08,187
And remember, that's the Buddha's approach to things.

116
00:11:08,246 --> 00:11:12,451
He's not interested in why something's happened, but how something's happened.

117
00:11:12,888 --> 00:11:18,195
Because in seeing how we create suffering for ourselves, we should be able to undo the not.

118
00:11:18,215 --> 00:11:20,236
We should be able to undo the process.

119
00:11:21,418 --> 00:11:21,599
Yeah.

120
00:11:25,203 --> 00:11:26,525
Is that alright?

121
00:11:27,125 --> 00:11:29,089
Yeah, pass.

122
00:11:29,109 --> 00:11:30,870
Nine out of ten.

123
00:11:33,894 --> 00:11:36,217
Ah, this is a tricky question.

124
00:11:36,859 --> 00:11:38,541
How can awareness be deluded?

125
00:11:40,376 --> 00:11:41,437
if it's unconditioned.

126
00:11:44,241 --> 00:11:54,936
This is one of the, you know, I don't think, I'm no great scholar, you know, and I can't say I've read all the scriptures.

127
00:11:54,956 --> 00:11:55,878
I've read the main ones.

128
00:11:56,839 --> 00:12:01,264
I don't think this question ever actually comes up in the scriptures.

129
00:12:01,424 --> 00:12:03,668
I must ask a scholar sometimes.

130
00:12:08,490 --> 00:12:18,706
The question of being unconditioned is not relevant to whether the awareness is wise or deluded.

131
00:12:19,166 --> 00:12:20,388
It's simply unconditioned.

132
00:12:22,792 --> 00:12:31,443
The unconditioned is referring mainly to the fact that it is not dependent on anything.

133
00:12:32,048 --> 00:12:36,113
It has its own existence, it has its own being.

134
00:12:36,653 --> 00:12:45,684
I'm using words very loosely here, right, because you know the Buddha doesn't like to talk about the qualities of the unconditioned.

135
00:12:45,705 --> 00:12:48,248
He just points to them.

136
00:12:48,609 --> 00:12:59,101
He points to them with sort of metaphor too, like the island, the refuge, etc., etc.

137
00:13:00,061 --> 00:13:20,033
as to how the awareness appears in a deluded state and then moves towards a wise state, as to why that happens, I don't think that's ever discussed.

138
00:13:20,053 --> 00:13:26,625
The only thing that's ever discussed is how to do that, but not why.

139
00:13:26,926 --> 00:13:32,235
So there's never any, to use a big word, ontological question in Buddhism.

140
00:13:32,755 --> 00:13:38,044
There's no question about why something has come to be in that ultimate sense.

141
00:13:39,167 --> 00:13:44,174
So there's no questions about why it was created in the first place.

142
00:13:45,370 --> 00:13:46,071
Anything like that.

143
00:13:46,652 --> 00:13:50,077
He shies off all those sorts of questions.

144
00:13:50,097 --> 00:13:54,907
Anything to do with metaphysics, he doesn't answer.

145
00:13:54,927 --> 00:13:55,948
He says it's a waste of time.

146
00:13:57,211 --> 00:14:02,760
So this is put in the famous quadrilemma, not the dilemma, quadrilemma.

147
00:14:02,780 --> 00:14:06,466
So the four main questions, as I'm sure you know, does the Buddha...

148
00:14:06,447 --> 00:14:08,269
On his death, does he exist?

149
00:14:08,750 --> 00:14:09,731
Does he not exist?

150
00:14:10,352 --> 00:14:12,495
Does he both exist and not exist?

151
00:14:12,897 --> 00:14:15,640
And does he neither not exist or exist?

152
00:14:16,001 --> 00:14:19,647
I mean, it just goes on and on, these negatives.

153
00:14:19,667 --> 00:14:21,429
Neither exist nor not exist.

154
00:14:21,850 --> 00:14:23,173
So does he exist?

155
00:14:23,732 --> 00:14:24,534
Does he continue?

156
00:14:24,855 --> 00:14:25,777
Does he not exist?

157
00:14:26,677 --> 00:14:30,102
Does he both somehow exist and not exist?

158
00:14:30,524 --> 00:14:33,889
And does he neither exist nor not exist?

159
00:14:35,741 --> 00:14:37,384
And the Buddha, of course, is silent.

160
00:14:38,225 --> 00:14:42,328
He says it's not a question that leads anywhere.

161
00:14:42,349 --> 00:14:44,371
It's just the intellect thinking, thinking.

162
00:14:48,615 --> 00:14:55,703
But what we do know is that we are deluded in his terms.

163
00:14:56,404 --> 00:15:01,070
And the delusion lies at its base in identity.

164
00:15:01,910 --> 00:15:03,893
We identify with this form

165
00:15:04,312 --> 00:15:28,176
it leads us into all sorts of mess and every time we move back into that position of the observer unwittingly even if we're not fully aware of it we're disidentifying as soon as something's an object you can't be it see and that's one of the things that we can say to ourselves we can sort of reflect upon it in the meditation we can look at something

166
00:15:28,476 --> 00:15:34,725
an image in the mind, an emotion, and say, well, you know, I'm looking at it.

167
00:15:34,784 --> 00:15:35,525
It can't be me.

168
00:15:37,427 --> 00:15:40,292
And then, of course, you abandon thinking and just watch.

169
00:15:41,312 --> 00:15:53,148
Because even that thought is stopping us from having a direct experience of not me, not mine.

170
00:15:53,168 --> 00:15:56,491
So there's no answer to that question.

171
00:15:56,927 --> 00:16:03,515
Can I ask, what does it mean, can awareness be deluded?

172
00:16:03,535 --> 00:16:12,628
I can't quite... Is there an example where one says, oh, my awareness is deluded?

173
00:16:13,849 --> 00:16:17,994
Well, awareness here is short for intuitive awareness.

174
00:16:19,275 --> 00:16:26,664
And the delusion in the Buddhist terms is that it doesn't see these three characteristics clearly.

175
00:16:27,269 --> 00:16:28,130
It doesn't see.

176
00:16:28,171 --> 00:16:35,143
Because it's so committed to this life form, it doesn't really catch impermanence.

177
00:16:36,245 --> 00:16:45,581
And although we in our practice get down to this business of arising and passing away of a breath and all that, remember the real point of impermanence is death.

178
00:16:46,051 --> 00:16:49,456
I mean, that really manifests our impermanence.

179
00:16:51,778 --> 00:16:53,981
And it's one place we don't like to go.

180
00:16:54,081 --> 00:16:59,289
I mean, you know, it's something that's going to happen to everybody else and maybe to me at some point in the future.

181
00:17:00,991 --> 00:17:01,972
So that's impermanence.

182
00:17:02,995 --> 00:17:13,189
And we do what we can to ignore it, to entertain ourselves away from it.

183
00:17:15,058 --> 00:17:18,703
There's a fantastic book called The Denial of Death.

184
00:17:19,325 --> 00:17:20,866
Name's just flitted through my mind.

185
00:17:22,128 --> 00:17:26,114
And it's a classic.

186
00:17:26,173 --> 00:17:28,057
It was written, I think, in the 70s or 80s.

187
00:17:29,057 --> 00:17:32,742
And the effect of the denial of death is unbelievable.

188
00:17:34,566 --> 00:17:35,507
Makes us run, you see.

189
00:17:35,948 --> 00:17:38,330
Makes us accumulate, etc.

190
00:17:41,355 --> 00:17:41,454
Yeah.

191
00:17:44,759 --> 00:17:55,674
So, this intuitive awareness, because of its identity with this form, doesn't see impermanence directly.

192
00:17:56,115 --> 00:17:58,598
It sees it superficially, day and night and all that.

193
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:01,923
It doesn't really see the cause of suffering.

194
00:18:03,929 --> 00:18:04,931
It doesn't really see it.

195
00:18:05,832 --> 00:18:12,262
And if it does see it, it is a break, but it finds it very difficult to let go of it.

196
00:18:13,845 --> 00:18:18,814
I mean, one example which I often use is smoking.

197
00:18:19,434 --> 00:18:25,144
So in the 50s, it was still understood that smoking was okay, didn't do much harm.

198
00:18:25,124 --> 00:18:30,191
Then as the science came through and people realised they were killing themselves, they didn't stop smoking.

199
00:18:31,092 --> 00:18:34,395
They just couldn't stop the process.

200
00:18:34,435 --> 00:18:47,813
So it's like with us, we can see the process of craving and we can see it's doing us harm, but it's very difficult to stop going for that tenth biscuit.

201
00:18:48,673 --> 00:18:49,115
You know what I mean?

202
00:18:49,134 --> 00:18:50,777
It's like...

203
00:18:52,022 --> 00:19:01,232
And that's the power of our cravings, which is the psychological cause of our suffering, craving.

204
00:19:01,713 --> 00:19:17,270
Sometimes, I mean, sometimes I talk about it as desire because I always think craving is far too strong a word because it covers the whole range of simple wrong desires to great big wrong desires.

205
00:19:17,707 --> 00:19:30,535
But remember that desire in English covers also all those beautiful things that we ought to desire, arising out of our social virtues, love, compassion, joy and so on.

206
00:19:33,670 --> 00:19:37,635
And when it's the not-self, then that's what it doesn't know.

207
00:19:38,438 --> 00:19:42,044
Because of that wrong identity, it's lost its own identity.

208
00:19:42,664 --> 00:19:45,690
It's lost its own sense of what it is.

209
00:19:46,431 --> 00:19:52,861
Now, whether it ever had that, it's difficult to say.

210
00:19:52,881 --> 00:19:58,851
I can't see it ever having had that in some other rebirth, in some other place.

211
00:19:59,184 --> 00:20:00,006
and have lost it.

212
00:20:00,826 --> 00:20:03,210
See, I can't see that happening.

213
00:20:04,391 --> 00:20:17,406
So it's going back to that question of time, of the origin of awareness, of how it arose in the first place.

214
00:20:17,426 --> 00:20:18,367
It's just unanswerable.

215
00:20:19,910 --> 00:20:22,272
All we know is that

216
00:20:23,401 --> 00:20:27,027
We aren't happy in that absolute fundamental way.

217
00:20:28,288 --> 00:20:29,932
That is an alienation with life.

218
00:20:30,092 --> 00:20:33,416
We don't feel we fit completely in with life.

219
00:20:33,877 --> 00:20:41,190
And what tells us that is, of course, the body falls ill and you die because you don't want to do that, really.

220
00:20:41,170 --> 00:20:42,751
Usually, you know.

221
00:20:42,791 --> 00:20:47,916
I mean, Jesus says it in that lovely poetic way, doesn't he?

222
00:20:47,936 --> 00:20:54,084
The birds have their nests, the fox has its holes and the birds their nests, but man has nowhere to rest his head.

223
00:20:54,824 --> 00:20:58,508
So we're always out of sync with nature.

224
00:21:00,750 --> 00:21:09,759
We're not like animals that are very in the moment in that sort of totally immersive, deluded way.

225
00:21:10,127 --> 00:21:11,489
But they are at home.

226
00:21:11,710 --> 00:21:15,733
This is where it makes, for want of a better word, it makes sense to them.

227
00:21:16,934 --> 00:21:18,635
They don't think about death.

228
00:21:18,916 --> 00:21:27,164
You never see sheep or cows having philosophical arguments as to whether they could do something about this problem.

229
00:21:32,369 --> 00:21:37,275
So yeah, there's no answer to the origins of awareness.

230
00:21:37,355 --> 00:21:39,477
All we know is that...

231
00:21:41,396 --> 00:21:42,218
It's within us.

232
00:21:42,778 --> 00:21:43,819
We experience it.

233
00:21:45,161 --> 00:21:48,904
And through our practice, we're slowly isolating its qualities.

234
00:21:49,705 --> 00:21:59,336
It's individuating out of the mass of those five aggregates, psychophysical organisms.

235
00:21:59,355 --> 00:22:01,719
People who have had an out-of-body experience, they know that.

236
00:22:02,118 --> 00:22:08,066
It's a very clear experience.

237
00:22:08,086 --> 00:22:10,407
Do you not see animals grieving death?

238
00:22:12,278 --> 00:22:14,121
They do, don't they?

239
00:22:14,141 --> 00:22:14,982
They're higher animals.

240
00:22:15,163 --> 00:22:19,750
Elephants and the higher apes.

241
00:22:20,111 --> 00:22:20,711
Yeah, it's true.

242
00:22:21,192 --> 00:22:24,798
Would that not suggest that they have an understanding of death?

243
00:22:24,818 --> 00:22:26,561
I don't know whether they have an understanding of death.

244
00:22:26,663 --> 00:22:31,250
It's probably the sense of... Well, understanding in the sense that they know that's a corpse now.

245
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:33,513
It's not... Yeah.

246
00:22:33,534 --> 00:22:33,914
Yeah.

247
00:22:34,621 --> 00:22:44,790
I mean, you know, it's becoming more and more obvious as they study the higher animals that they're far more intelligent than we would presume, you know.

248
00:22:50,436 --> 00:22:50,656
Yeah.

249
00:22:52,118 --> 00:22:52,679
Higher apes.

250
00:22:54,981 --> 00:22:58,585
Elephants grieve, don't they?

251
00:22:58,605 --> 00:23:01,167
So all animals except elephants and...

252
00:23:08,269 --> 00:23:28,692
it's a spectrum isn't it and then something happened to a particular ape and we went into a different category yeah

253
00:23:34,392 --> 00:23:43,622
Is the insight into the true nature of ourselves, but can't that change?

254
00:23:43,701 --> 00:23:46,305
Or is it an insight into the world and others?

255
00:23:50,128 --> 00:23:54,034
Well, these insights are accumulative.

256
00:23:55,375 --> 00:23:58,137
As soon as you hear them,

257
00:23:58,607 --> 00:24:02,657
the Buddha's message about anicca, dukkha, and atta.

258
00:24:02,919 --> 00:24:10,436
Like there's a click, our awareness or our relationship to the world just clicks.

259
00:24:10,616 --> 00:24:15,789
It's clicking every time you have a sort of new understanding of things.

260
00:24:16,411 --> 00:24:21,217
Even at an intellectual level, you can have a different view of something.

261
00:24:22,337 --> 00:24:25,862
And this feeds into your attitude and how you speak.

262
00:24:25,902 --> 00:24:27,223
That's the A4 path, you see.

263
00:24:28,164 --> 00:24:33,451
So all our insights are slowly changing our relationship to the world.

264
00:24:34,152 --> 00:24:42,942
And it's moving us towards this position of the world is not me, it's not mine, but I have to be engaged in it.

265
00:24:44,557 --> 00:24:50,826
And the reason you want to be engaged in it is because you've made a connection with other beings.

266
00:24:53,569 --> 00:24:55,573
You're drawn by compassion.

267
00:24:55,593 --> 00:25:03,784
Compassion is understood to be, the Buddha talks about, like a little, a trembling in the heart when you see other people suffering.

268
00:25:03,804 --> 00:25:04,845
And it draws you.

269
00:25:06,406 --> 00:25:08,109
That would be a certain sorrow.

270
00:25:09,111 --> 00:25:12,855
And if you don't react to it, it remains unrequited.

271
00:25:12,955 --> 00:25:13,636
It remains...

272
00:25:14,089 --> 00:25:21,741
within you and you might feel guilty or you might feel sad that you didn't respond at the right time.

273
00:25:22,462 --> 00:25:25,086
And that's just a natural thing that happens.

274
00:25:25,728 --> 00:25:27,691
I don't think you have to work at it.

275
00:25:28,311 --> 00:25:34,560
It just comes with an insight into ourselves.

276
00:25:34,601 --> 00:25:36,144
It's a universal insight.

277
00:25:36,163 --> 00:25:37,526
These are universal insights.

278
00:25:38,686 --> 00:25:40,349
All human beings are capable of.

279
00:25:43,891 --> 00:25:46,994
The insight itself doesn't change.

280
00:25:47,015 --> 00:25:48,477
You just get further insights.

281
00:25:48,537 --> 00:25:50,318
It accumulates.

282
00:25:52,461 --> 00:26:01,231
So in these four stages of liberation, the stream entrance, the Buddha says it's just like a flash of lightning.

283
00:26:01,833 --> 00:26:04,695
The person sees everything, but it's like that was it.

284
00:26:05,978 --> 00:26:09,662
It's not really a full grasp of the situation.

285
00:26:11,109 --> 00:26:14,554
And the second one, I think he says, it's like a full starry night.

286
00:26:15,576 --> 00:26:19,240
Again, there's a deeper seeing, but it's not complete.

287
00:26:20,300 --> 00:26:22,344
And the third one is like a full moon night.

288
00:26:22,944 --> 00:26:26,028
So in the East, you can see color, it's very bright.

289
00:26:27,390 --> 00:26:31,915
And then you don't get to see the world like the sun until you finally cracked it.

290
00:26:32,737 --> 00:26:37,021
So it's a slow, but the insights are always the same.

291
00:26:37,182 --> 00:26:39,345
They're always around in permanence.

292
00:26:40,439 --> 00:26:57,569
creative the creation of suffering through wrong relationship desire or craving and not self it's always the same thing so you know there's nothing what once you've understood that there's like there's nothing more to be known there's only the practice

293
00:27:05,616 --> 00:27:14,311
I mean, that's why people can be fully liberated who in society are considered to be dull-minded.

294
00:27:15,034 --> 00:27:16,717
Because you don't need the intellect.

295
00:27:18,219 --> 00:27:26,493
What you need is the liberation of the intuitive awareness, the intuitive intelligence from its confusion with the intellect.

296
00:27:26,997 --> 00:27:39,449
And in fact, people who are intellectual, people who are intellectual or even those lost in art are less well disposed.

297
00:27:40,230 --> 00:27:53,942
So there's the story that runs with the Dhammapada of a monk who had disciples and all his disciples, something like 10 of them or something, all became liberated and he wasn't.

298
00:27:54,202 --> 00:27:56,885
And he was a teacher and he knew everything.

299
00:27:57,929 --> 00:28:08,603
So he thought, well, and he sort of bit the bullet and he went to see one of them and he said, could you teach me how to become fully literate?

300
00:28:08,623 --> 00:28:11,547
And the fellow knew this guy was too intellectually conceited.

301
00:28:11,567 --> 00:28:12,327
He couldn't help him.

302
00:28:12,347 --> 00:28:17,634
So he told him, well, actually, the person you want to see is this other past student of yours.

303
00:28:17,914 --> 00:28:19,616
And so he's passed on down the line.

304
00:28:19,596 --> 00:28:26,727
And he got to this point where this monk said to him, well, you need to work with this boy.

305
00:28:26,767 --> 00:28:27,387
He'll show you.

306
00:28:27,407 --> 00:28:31,472
So this little child, you see, and the little child took him to an anthill.

307
00:28:31,733 --> 00:28:32,535
Do you know this story?

308
00:28:33,276 --> 00:28:33,596
No.

309
00:28:33,615 --> 00:28:39,765
He took him to an anthill and he said, now in an anthill, when the ants leave, a snake often lives in it.

310
00:28:40,465 --> 00:28:46,413
And he said, supposing this anthill has six holes, how would you get the snake out?

311
00:28:47,305 --> 00:28:50,288
And he said, well, you'd stop up five holes, you see.

312
00:28:50,829 --> 00:28:52,030
And the boy said, yeah, very good.

313
00:28:54,094 --> 00:28:56,837
So you stop the five senses and watch the mind.

314
00:28:57,337 --> 00:29:00,423
And of course, in no length of time, he became fully liberated.

315
00:29:00,442 --> 00:29:11,738
And his problem was conceit, thinking that because he'd understood something so well, he must be liberated from delusion.

316
00:29:12,618 --> 00:29:14,500
And that's what the intellect can do.

317
00:29:14,540 --> 00:29:15,742
It can fool you.

318
00:29:27,383 --> 00:29:32,771
So the question is, is the insight into the nature of ourselves, but can it change?

319
00:29:33,353 --> 00:29:34,776
Yeah, the insights grow.

320
00:29:34,816 --> 00:29:36,578
Look at it that way.

321
00:29:36,618 --> 00:29:43,671
They expand, they accumulate, they develop one on top of the other.

322
00:29:43,651 --> 00:30:07,666
uh insight into the world and others remember in the buddha's teaching the world whenever he talks about the world he's talking about the world we're creating he's not talking about the scientific world the objective world right it's not that it doesn't come up that you know the world out there and all that but when he's talking spiritually it's always the world that we're creating through these through this organism

323
00:30:10,616 --> 00:30:18,270
in this world, in this fathom-length body is suffering and the end of suffering.

324
00:30:18,291 --> 00:30:19,053
Yeah, is that right?

325
00:30:22,539 --> 00:30:25,625
Is there a fundamental difference between men and women?

326
00:30:27,990 --> 00:30:29,132
In your experience?

327
00:30:32,268 --> 00:30:43,522
Um, there's definitely, I think, uh, you've got to be careful because, uh, some women shade into, uh, let's talk about masculine and feminine.

328
00:30:43,823 --> 00:30:48,990
Some feminine types move into the masculine and some masculine types move.

329
00:30:49,009 --> 00:31:00,704
So there's always that, you know, uh, but if we talk about the two extremes, uh, when I was in, I used to, uh, when I, I mean, I still teach in Dublin, but, uh,

330
00:31:01,106 --> 00:31:05,373
There was a time when I used to stay with a very elderly lady called Beatrice.

331
00:31:06,354 --> 00:31:09,598
And she was blind from diabetes.

332
00:31:09,618 --> 00:31:11,401
She'd lost her husband, her two sons.

333
00:31:13,022 --> 00:31:14,565
And she was an extraordinary person.

334
00:31:15,105 --> 00:31:16,448
A lovely feel about her.

335
00:31:18,530 --> 00:31:19,932
And we got to a conversation.

336
00:31:20,373 --> 00:31:27,383
And if I remember rightly, it was about... We got into a conversation.

337
00:31:27,762 --> 00:31:29,005
And she said to me...

338
00:31:30,352 --> 00:31:34,856
you know why we're, we weren't arguing, but you know what, why we're taking different positions.

339
00:31:35,278 --> 00:31:35,778
And I said, no.

340
00:31:36,239 --> 00:31:40,243
He says, well, men think deductively and women think inductively.

341
00:31:40,805 --> 00:31:42,787
And I said, no, that's interesting, Beatrice.

342
00:31:42,807 --> 00:31:43,728
I said, well, what does that mean?

343
00:31:44,108 --> 00:31:49,454
Because I couldn't, I couldn't remember what deductive and inductive thinking was.

344
00:31:49,474 --> 00:32:00,087
And she said, well, the feminine, I'm paraphrasing, the feminine takes the particular and from the particular produces a concept.

345
00:32:00,929 --> 00:32:05,334
Whereas the masculine starts from the concept and draws it down to the particular.

346
00:32:09,638 --> 00:32:12,382
Later on, we were talking about the war in Afghanistan.

347
00:32:12,402 --> 00:32:14,763
So that's when I was with her.

348
00:32:15,986 --> 00:32:21,531
And I suddenly, we were talking about it and I suddenly sort of went, we're doing it, aren't we Beatrice?

349
00:32:21,551 --> 00:32:22,893
She says, yes, you do it naturally.

350
00:32:23,574 --> 00:32:24,935
She says, you don't know you're doing it.

351
00:32:25,276 --> 00:32:27,038
It's just the way you think.

352
00:32:28,182 --> 00:32:37,460
So from a feminine point of view, when they look at a war, they see people being blown to bits, dead.

353
00:32:38,121 --> 00:32:41,989
So the obvious conclusion is we mustn't fight a war.

354
00:32:43,336 --> 00:32:48,724
From the deductive masculine point of view, there's the bigger picture, right?

355
00:32:48,865 --> 00:32:50,347
We've got to get rid of these terrorists.

356
00:32:50,848 --> 00:32:55,758
So those people become collateral, right?

357
00:32:55,778 --> 00:32:59,523
They become part and parcel of this greater view.

358
00:33:00,306 --> 00:33:07,317
And so in a patriarchal society, women are stupid because they can't see the bigger picture.

359
00:33:08,647 --> 00:33:17,596
But what happens is that then you have a patriarchal society that loses contact with the suffering, with the actual what's actually going on.

360
00:33:19,838 --> 00:33:25,663
So that is quite a distinction on the ends of the spectrum.

361
00:33:29,067 --> 00:33:30,189
The other one is will.

362
00:33:32,911 --> 00:33:35,854
The masculine will is the will of the storm.

363
00:33:36,559 --> 00:33:39,624
Whereas the feminine will is the will of the mountain.

364
00:33:41,905 --> 00:33:46,050
And my parents were like that.

365
00:33:46,192 --> 00:33:50,537
My father was, you know, a sort of a get-things-done.

366
00:33:50,576 --> 00:34:00,008
And when my mother didn't want to do what he wanted to do, she just simply said, no.

367
00:34:00,689 --> 00:34:01,169
And that was it.

368
00:34:02,009 --> 00:34:04,153
He couldn't move her.

369
00:34:05,263 --> 00:34:07,709
Olivia Rao, she got away.

370
00:34:08,210 --> 00:34:09,833
No.

371
00:34:09,853 --> 00:34:11,615
The mountain does not move.

372
00:34:13,960 --> 00:34:18,088
Emotionally, that's also quite a distinction on the far ends.

373
00:34:19,349 --> 00:34:23,538
A man, the masculine, experiences emotions in the head.

374
00:34:25,722 --> 00:34:27,204
I often have that with meditators.

375
00:34:28,163 --> 00:34:29,465
When they're angry, it's up here.

376
00:34:30,528 --> 00:34:31,010
Anger's up here.

377
00:34:31,030 --> 00:34:33,476
The fear's, it's all up here, you know.

378
00:34:34,538 --> 00:34:38,628
Whereas the feminine will feel it in the body as an emotion.

379
00:34:39,951 --> 00:34:45,565
And in my own case, I remember I had this insight and

380
00:34:46,304 --> 00:34:48,166
which was, you know, it changed my life.

381
00:34:48,646 --> 00:34:55,431
And I remember my next task, it came up to me and said, my next task is, what is an emotion?

382
00:34:56,112 --> 00:35:01,318
So I was 25 years old and I'm asking myself, now what is an emotion?

383
00:35:01,338 --> 00:35:02,838
Because up until then, it was always up here.

384
00:35:03,460 --> 00:35:07,043
You know, it was just, there was no distinction between the thought and the emotion.

385
00:35:07,483 --> 00:35:10,126
And I had just no contact with the body as such.

386
00:35:11,806 --> 00:35:14,909
So in meditation, in terms of the practice,

387
00:35:16,222 --> 00:35:23,673
The masculine has to come into the body to feel emotions for the first time sometimes as real feelings in the body.

388
00:35:24,735 --> 00:35:35,311
And for the feminine, because they're so locked into emotion, they have to lose their connection with emotion as emotion.

389
00:35:36,085 --> 00:35:47,663
And the process then is to go down to the sensations, the four Mahabhuta, to see that an emotion isn't real.

390
00:35:48,304 --> 00:35:50,807
It's just feeling, it's just sensation.

391
00:35:53,132 --> 00:35:56,878
So that's one sort of distinction.

392
00:36:00,182 --> 00:36:05,715
These are all generalizations, you understand.

393
00:36:05,735 --> 00:36:18,005
So yeah, I think the masculine feminine view of life is different, a different experience.

394
00:36:30,135 --> 00:36:34,505
Yeah.

395
00:36:35,027 --> 00:36:43,226
After all the chatter of the mind has quietened down, a sense of self remains.

396
00:36:43,246 --> 00:36:48,398
Talk a bit about this perception that I am in my head looking out at the world.

397
00:36:48,378 --> 00:37:05,492
yes just to remind you because I think most of you know my imagery around this around the most obvious one I suppose is looking into a shop window and

398
00:37:07,108 --> 00:37:20,090
So as you look into the window and looking at the things there that you might want to buy, you suddenly become aware that there's a mirror image and you catch yourself looking into the window.

399
00:37:21,693 --> 00:37:26,501
So that window pane you could see as a sort of screen.

400
00:37:27,358 --> 00:37:54,987
and all the light from the shop is moving out onto that screen and that's what you're looking at but the screen also is catching your image looking into the screen so that's consciousness so when you're in that position of the observer the knower and you become aware of it

401
00:37:56,974 --> 00:38:04,126
The object that you're seeing, the sense of self, the observer, is also an object.

402
00:38:06,190 --> 00:38:11,838
Everything that we're experiencing from that position of the observer is an object.

403
00:38:11,918 --> 00:38:19,831
So pain in my knee, emotions, an image in my mind, they all become an object because I can actually point to them.

404
00:38:20,231 --> 00:38:21,594
I can give them names.

405
00:38:21,914 --> 00:38:22,155
Yeah.

406
00:38:23,958 --> 00:38:36,675
And when I become aware of being the observer, of being the one who knows, then somehow that sense of self, that sense of the feeler, is also an object.

407
00:38:36,695 --> 00:38:37,838
So I can't be that either.

408
00:38:42,864 --> 00:38:51,838
Now at that point, you can stay there and just sense that sense of presence as an object, a sense of presence.

409
00:38:52,324 --> 00:38:59,096
But it's telling you something about this quality of intuitive awareness.

410
00:39:00,918 --> 00:39:06,166
You know, what are you actually experiencing when you're in that very clear state of the observer?

411
00:39:08,411 --> 00:39:16,222
And in Mahayana sometimes they tell you to sort of glance back, as it were, glance back into the observing state.

412
00:39:17,670 --> 00:39:19,934
And then when you've done that, you can reflect.

413
00:39:20,817 --> 00:39:21,878
Was there a body there?

414
00:39:21,938 --> 00:39:24,804
Was there any feelings, sensations, emotions, what was in it?

415
00:39:26,306 --> 00:39:37,467
So again, it's these little insights, little seeings that begin to change our relationship.

416
00:39:43,438 --> 00:39:55,503
Of course, you can pull yourself out of all these different selves, an emotional self, a thought self, a job self, a relationship self.

417
00:39:55,523 --> 00:40:00,072
You can pull yourself out to this business of the observer, but you can't get rid of that self.

418
00:40:03,219 --> 00:40:05,143
Can't get rid of that self.

419
00:40:05,663 --> 00:40:08,407
Now consciousness is arising and passing away.

420
00:40:08,728 --> 00:40:10,190
It's not steady.

421
00:40:10,871 --> 00:40:14,336
It's not something that is always there.

422
00:40:15,057 --> 00:40:18,041
It disappears in sleep, for instance.

423
00:40:18,061 --> 00:40:32,565
And in Abhidhamma they say these consciousnesses are flashing at an enormous rate, picking up information from various senses so fast that it gives us that sense of continuity and also a certain combination

424
00:40:32,983 --> 00:40:37,088
So you're hearing and seeing at the same time, but not in Buddhist psychology.

425
00:40:37,469 --> 00:40:40,231
There's one consciousness seeing and one consciousness hearing.

426
00:40:41,233 --> 00:40:46,177
And it's happening so fast that it creates this illusion.

427
00:40:48,940 --> 00:40:58,771
Now, being aware of that self, the consciousness that that sense of self is arising in is also still arising and passing away.

428
00:41:04,608 --> 00:41:09,637
And if you keep your eye there sort of long enough, you might catch that.

429
00:41:15,547 --> 00:41:29,771
So in terms of this, yeah, so in terms of the question, that perception of self-awareness

430
00:41:30,916 --> 00:41:33,918
is telling us something about the nature of awareness.

431
00:41:34,480 --> 00:41:35,340
It's emptiness.

432
00:41:35,802 --> 00:41:37,384
So you get this word emptiness.

433
00:41:38,625 --> 00:41:41,829
The awareness is empty of all phenomena.

434
00:41:42,590 --> 00:41:48,817
It's empty of whatever the psychophysical organism manifests.

435
00:41:49,356 --> 00:41:50,559
That's what it's empty of.

436
00:41:52,981 --> 00:41:55,824
Yeah?

437
00:41:55,844 --> 00:41:58,407
But of course, what you're beginning to experience,

438
00:41:59,215 --> 00:42:02,639
When we're in the position of the self-awareness, that is the real.

439
00:42:04,663 --> 00:42:12,554
Everything else is an object of awareness arising and passing away, but this awareness seems to be there all the time.

440
00:42:17,001 --> 00:42:17,201
Yeah?

441
00:42:23,088 --> 00:42:23,429
Maybe.

442
00:42:23,469 --> 00:42:28,958
Any questions around that?

443
00:42:29,077 --> 00:42:29,137
No?

444
00:42:29,793 --> 00:42:39,362
I mean, later on, if other questions come up, you can write them down again, yeah?

445
00:42:39,382 --> 00:42:44,327
The last one is, you commented that porridge itself has no taste.

446
00:42:45,188 --> 00:42:53,836
Were you referring to the conditions of sense object, sense base and sense consciousness needing to be present in order for the sense contact and perception to arise?

447
00:42:57,159 --> 00:42:59,782
Yes.

448
00:42:59,998 --> 00:43:14,141
The sense base has this sensitivity to, in this case, chemicals in the eyes to amazingly subatomic particles, for heaven's sake, photons.

449
00:43:14,181 --> 00:43:18,628
The ear sense base is sensitive to pressure.

450
00:43:19,269 --> 00:43:20,311
So they're all sensitive.

451
00:43:21,934 --> 00:43:25,500
But then as that information is taken into the mind,

452
00:43:25,682 --> 00:43:30,148
then the mind plays with it and creates something.

453
00:43:31,150 --> 00:43:50,137
So if you make a determination before you fall asleep that you will see the process of hearing when you wake up, you'll see that the bell, the first sign of the bell is just pressure, like as if your hands are touching like that.

454
00:43:51,077 --> 00:43:54,001
And then as it's taken in, you get the sound.

455
00:43:55,282 --> 00:43:58,945
And then the sound is given a name, bell.

456
00:43:59,706 --> 00:44:02,168
Then it's given a purpose, alarm bell.

457
00:44:02,628 --> 00:44:05,550
And then it's given the person, me.

458
00:44:05,751 --> 00:44:06,411
I've got to get up.

459
00:44:07,233 --> 00:44:08,393
It's right at the end of the process.

460
00:44:09,335 --> 00:44:11,797
Right at the end of the process.

461
00:44:11,817 --> 00:44:13,297
So it's the same with all the senses.

462
00:44:14,398 --> 00:44:19,824
It's always being taken into the mind and then the mind makes sense of it.

463
00:44:20,445 --> 00:44:25,068
But at the sense base, it's just very simple information coming in.

464
00:44:28,643 --> 00:44:38,514
You might have seen those photographs of how the eye moves around a picture when it's looking at a piece of art, for instance, in an art gallery.

465
00:44:39,476 --> 00:44:47,244
And the eye is moving at tremendous rate all over the place, you know, and often centering on something that you're particularly interested in.

466
00:44:47,625 --> 00:44:48,565
But you don't see that.

467
00:44:48,686 --> 00:44:54,713
What you see is the picture.

468
00:44:56,775 --> 00:44:58,498
So the porridge...

469
00:44:58,916 --> 00:45:01,965
is only offering you chemicals, yeah?

470
00:45:02,766 --> 00:45:10,969
And the tongue and the nose are sensing it and then it's going in and then there's all this mental stuff going on around porridge.

471
00:45:13,396 --> 00:45:18,784
And there was a program I saw where the process of smelling is also at a subatomic level.

472
00:45:19,666 --> 00:45:21,248
I can't tell you how that is.

473
00:45:23,791 --> 00:45:29,161
But it's not a simple case of a cell touching a chemical.

474
00:45:29,641 --> 00:45:31,764
It's actually happening at an atomic level.

475
00:45:32,585 --> 00:45:33,086
Remarkable.

476
00:45:35,710 --> 00:45:36,972
So the next...

477
00:45:38,742 --> 00:45:45,530
Part of the question is, this reminds me of the question, if a tree falls in the forest and no one hears it, does it make a sound?

478
00:45:46,391 --> 00:45:49,536
I guess the answer is no, in the absence of an ear and ear consciousness.

479
00:45:49,936 --> 00:45:52,981
But if you leave a tape recorder in the forest, it picks up the noise.

480
00:45:53,681 --> 00:45:56,726
Can you comment on this?

481
00:45:56,746 --> 00:46:04,277
Well, human beings are incredibly clever at extending tools

482
00:46:04,391 --> 00:46:05,512
All animals use tools.

483
00:46:05,532 --> 00:46:12,860
I just read an article here about a puffin that picks up a stick in order to scratch itself.

484
00:46:12,880 --> 00:46:22,530
So it seems even birds, which are dinosaurs, could actually use tools, but they can't develop it.

485
00:46:22,791 --> 00:46:28,677
They can't then think, oh, well, I'll sort of manufacture it as a steel object.

486
00:46:29,400 --> 00:46:34,527
So human beings have been able to extend through their imagination, et cetera, to extend too.

487
00:46:34,547 --> 00:46:42,195
So we have these massive machines that do all our heavy work for us, you know, and it's just an extension of an arm.

488
00:46:42,697 --> 00:46:50,186
I mean, our groundsman, Roy, if you ever see him moving his machine around, it really does look like his arm.

489
00:46:50,706 --> 00:46:54,190
He's got complete control over it as he's shifting soil here and there.

490
00:46:54,210 --> 00:46:55,172
It's quite remarkable.

491
00:46:56,713 --> 00:46:58,074
And all he's doing is this little business.

492
00:47:00,164 --> 00:47:09,956
When it comes to hearing things, of course, we've manufactured these gadgets that are sensitive to sound waves.

493
00:47:11,378 --> 00:47:11,800
That's all.

494
00:47:12,541 --> 00:47:13,581
There's nothing magical.

495
00:47:14,543 --> 00:47:15,284
It's not an ear.

496
00:47:15,724 --> 00:47:17,226
It's just sensitive to sound waves.

497
00:47:17,367 --> 00:47:18,768
And it repeats the sound waves.

498
00:47:19,250 --> 00:47:20,530
So it's the sound waves you're hearing.

499
00:47:21,532 --> 00:47:29,884
So the recorder has caught the pressure waves coming from the falling of the tree.

500
00:47:30,387 --> 00:47:35,914
And then he's able to repeat it so that you then hear the tree falling.

501
00:47:36,096 --> 00:47:38,518
But the recorder hasn't heard the tree falling.

502
00:47:39,059 --> 00:47:40,963
The recording has simply recorded these.

503
00:47:42,344 --> 00:47:45,190
Yeah.

504
00:47:45,329 --> 00:47:48,253
So it doesn't upset the Buddhist psychology.

505
00:47:51,398 --> 00:47:55,364
Porridge still has no taste and the tree doesn't make a sound.

506
00:47:56,476 --> 00:48:25,182
and there's the old Zen thing isn't it you see you know when I can't remember the story exactly there's a flag I think the student says to the master the flag is flying and the master says is the flag flying or your mind see so what are you actually seeing are you seeing the flag or are you seeing your mind that's one of these koans you see I think that's it

507
00:48:26,411 --> 00:48:39,510
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and I have not created even greater confusion and that you will through your arduous practice soon be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

